'''Neyrangistan, Hirbodistan, Hadokht Nask''' is a [[Zoroastrian]] [[religious book]] which is written in [[middle Persian|middle Persian language]].<ref name="Shz">{{Cite journal |last=Hashemi |first=Mahsa |last2=Najari |first2=Hossein | title=Avestan Architecture: A Descriptive Etymological Lexicon |url=https://www.scipress.com/ILSHS.63.59 |journal=International Letters of Social and Humanistic Sciences |publisher=SciPress Ltd., |publication-place=Switzerland |publication-date=2015 |volume=63 |pages=105-116 |doi=10.18052/www.scipress.com/ILSHS.63.105}}</ref> The book consists of three documents whose name is gathered from them. Neyrangistan, Hirbodistan, Hadokht Nask is an [[exegesis]] text of [[Avesta]] like the [[Zend]] and refers to the laws of the Zoroastrian tradition and the opinions of exegetes regarding the laws. The texts are probably written and collected by [[Saoshyant]] and [[Pishagsar]], two exegetes of the Avesta.<ref name="Thes">{{Cite thesis |last=Shapira |first=Dan |title=Studies in Zoroastrian Exegesis - Zand |degree=PhD |url=https://archive.org/details/StudiesInZoroastrianExegesis-Zand |language=English}}</ref> The latest available version of the book is edited in the 17th century.
